# Redis Data Structures

Redis provides specialized data structures beyond simple strings, each with dedicated commands optimized for specific access patterns. Choosing the right structure can reduce code complexity and improve performance by orders of magnitude. See [[redis#data-model]] for an overview of how these types map to keys and values.

## Strings

Strings are the simplest type — a key maps to a single value (up to 512MB). Beyond basic GET/SET (see [[redis/caching#get-set]]), strings support atomic counters and binary-safe storage.

```javascript
import Redis from "ioredis";
const redis = new Redis(process.env.REDIS_URL);

// Atomic counters
await redis.set("page:views", 0);
await redis.incr("page:views");           // 1
await redis.incrby("page:views", 10);     // 11
await redis.decr("page:views");           // 10
await redis.incrbyfloat("score", 1.5);    // 1.5

// Append to a string
await redis.append("log:entry", "line 1\n");
await redis.append("log:entry", "line 2\n");

// Get/set substring
await redis.setrange("greeting", 6, "Redis"); // "Hello Redis"
const sub = await redis.getrange("greeting", 0, 4); // "Hello"
```

## Lists

Ordered collections with O(1) push/pop at both ends. Ideal for queues, stacks, and recent item feeds.

```javascript
// Queue pattern (FIFO): push left, pop right
await redis.lpush("tasks", "task-1", "task-2", "task-3");
const nextTask = await redis.rpop("tasks"); // "task-1"

// Stack pattern (LIFO): push left, pop left
await redis.lpush("undo", "action-1", "action-2");
const lastAction = await redis.lpop("undo"); // "action-2"

// Blocking pop (wait for items, great for worker queues)
const [list, item] = await redis.brpop("tasks", 30); // block up to 30s

// Range queries
const recent = await redis.lrange("feed:user:1", 0, 9); // first 10 items
const length = await redis.llen("tasks");

// Trim to keep only recent items
await redis.ltrim("feed:user:1", 0, 99); // keep last 100
```

## Sets and Sorted Sets

### Sets

Unordered collections of unique members. Efficient for membership testing, tagging, and set operations.

```javascript
// Add members
await redis.sadd("tags:article:1", "redis", "database", "nosql");
await redis.sadd("tags:article:2", "redis", "caching", "performance");

// Membership test
const isMember = await redis.sismember("tags:article:1", "redis"); // 1 (true)

// Set operations
const intersection = await redis.sinter("tags:article:1", "tags:article:2"); // ["redis"]
const union = await redis.sunion("tags:article:1", "tags:article:2");
const diff = await redis.sdiff("tags:article:1", "tags:article:2"); // ["database", "nosql"]

// Random member
const random = await redis.srandmember("tags:article:1");
const allMembers = await redis.smembers("tags:article:1");
```

### Sorted Sets

Sets where each member has a score, enabling ranking and range queries. Perfect for leaderboards, rate limiting, and scheduled jobs.

```javascript
// Leaderboard
await redis.zadd("leaderboard", 1500, "alice", 1200, "bob", 1800, "carol");

// Top 3 (highest scores)
const top3 = await redis.zrevrange("leaderboard", 0, 2, "WITHSCORES");
// ["carol", "1800", "alice", "1500", "bob", "1200"]

// Rank lookup (0-based, highest first)
const rank = await redis.zrevrank("leaderboard", "alice"); // 1

// Score range
const midTier = await redis.zrangebyscore("leaderboard", 1000, 1600);

// Increment score
await redis.zincrby("leaderboard", 100, "bob"); // bob now 1300

// Rate limiting (sliding window)
const now = Date.now();
const windowMs = 60000;
await redis.zadd("ratelimit:user:1", now, `${now}`);
await redis.zremrangebyscore("ratelimit:user:1", 0, now - windowMs);
const requestCount = await redis.zcard("ratelimit:user:1");
```

## Hashes

Field-value maps within a single key. Ideal for storing objects without serialization overhead.

```javascript
// Store an object
await redis.hset("user:1001",
  "name", "Alice",
  "email", "alice@example.com",
  "role", "admin",
  "loginCount", "0"
);

// Get a single field
const name = await redis.hget("user:1001", "name"); // "Alice"

// Get multiple fields
const [email, role] = await redis.hmget("user:1001", "email", "role");

// Get all fields
const user = await redis.hgetall("user:1001");
// { name: "Alice", email: "alice@example.com", role: "admin", loginCount: "0" }

// Atomic increment on a hash field
await redis.hincrby("user:1001", "loginCount", 1);

// Check field existence
const exists = await redis.hexists("user:1001", "email"); // 1

// Delete a field
await redis.hdel("user:1001", "role");
```

## Bitmaps and HyperLogLog

### Bitmaps

Compact boolean arrays using string type. Each bit represents a flag. Extremely memory-efficient for large boolean datasets.

```javascript
// Track daily active users (bit position = user ID)
await redis.setbit("dau:2026-04-10", 1001, 1); // user 1001 active
await redis.setbit("dau:2026-04-10", 1002, 1); // user 1002 active

// Check if user was active
const wasActive = await redis.getbit("dau:2026-04-10", 1001); // 1

// Count active users
const activeCount = await redis.bitcount("dau:2026-04-10"); // 2

// Users active on both days (AND)
await redis.bitop("AND", "dau:both", "dau:2026-04-09", "dau:2026-04-10");

// Feature flags
await redis.setbit("features:dark-mode", 1001, 1); // enable for user 1001
```

### HyperLogLog

Probabilistic cardinality estimation using constant memory (~12KB regardless of set size). Accurate to within 0.81% standard error.

```javascript
// Count unique visitors
await redis.pfadd("visitors:2026-04-10", "user-a", "user-b", "user-c");
await redis.pfadd("visitors:2026-04-10", "user-a", "user-d"); // duplicates ignored

// Approximate count
const uniqueCount = await redis.pfcount("visitors:2026-04-10"); // ~4

// Merge multiple HyperLogLogs (weekly unique visitors)
await redis.pfmerge("visitors:week-15",
  "visitors:2026-04-06",
  "visitors:2026-04-07",
  "visitors:2026-04-08"
);
const weeklyUniques = await redis.pfcount("visitors:week-15");
```
